<p id="fs-id1165042681168">In the following exercises, consider Kepler&#8217;s equation regarding planetary orbits, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>&#949;</mi><mspace width="0.1em"/><mtext>sin</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>&#949;</mi><mspace width="0.1em"/><mtext>sin</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> where <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>M</mi></annotation-xml></semantics></math> is the mean anomaly, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>E</mi></annotation-xml></semantics></math> is eccentric anomaly, and <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>&#949;</mi></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>&#949;</mi></annotation-xml></semantics></math> measures eccentricity.</p>
<div data-type="exercise" id="fs-id1165043393688">
